title: Traxxas Rustler 1/10 Stadium Truck - Self Righting Skis

description.text:
Done...

Built and designed in AutoCAD, are a set of skis for my Traxxas Rustler XL (1/10 Scale Stadium Truck).

Here is an explanation of the files...

struts.stl - A set of struts to print alone to fit the size mentioned below.
struts_short.stl - A shorter set of struts, if you like the "highjack" look.
front.stl - The front split part of the ski (must be attached to the rest of the parts)
parts.stl - The rest of the parts of the skis
ski.stl - Full ski if your printer supports large prints
ski_complete.stl - A full model of the ski - NO SCALE
strut_complete.stl - A full model of the strut - NO SCALE (But matches the NO SCALE ski)

NOTE: The files listed at "no scale".

The ski's will be universal to whatever vehicle that you want them to be on, but the strut is designed to work with my truck and the way they need to attach to the chassis. Mine works as a simple removal of a tire versus some other designs that require a full change-out of the front end.

They are quite large, as you can imagine. Designed to be printed with a full length of 11.85 inches. This size, the struts will work with a standard 12MM hex hub and will require no other work, aside from a little cleaning up. If you change the size of the strut, you will have to remember to reposition the holes in the base so that they still attach to the skis correctly.

You will also need to find some small nuts and bolts to attach the parts together unless you want to use an alternate method to do so. I found some spares with my truck so I used them. NOTE - the struts need to be positioned with the flat face to the front. This allows the skis to rotate back into a good landing position if you happen to catch air.

All that being said - I started them. You are all welcome to do as you wish (except sell them, of course) to improve on the design.

Paddle tires on the back and skis on the front.

Enjoy! Now, bring on the snow! Merry Christmas!

My skis were printed using a Dremel Idea Printer with a 8x6x6 bed. I printed with 3 shells, 40% infill, a speed of 100 at a 220deg temp. I used PLA with mine, if it matters.

description.text:
Here are some tokens for the X-Wing miniatures game, to add a bit more flair and personality to your accessories. So far I've included tokens for Focus, Evade, Stress and Target Lock, since these are probably the most used ones. I may consider adding more for shields and a couple more in the future.

There are two version of each token. The standard ones have extra detail printed on top around the symbols, and the Alternate versions have the detail recessed into the token to make it easier to print the top if you want the symbol a different colour to the base.

They are pretty similar in size to the original tokens, but maybe a fraction bigger. If you use a custom token holder they may not fit very well. Print a couple to test first, otherwise you could scale them down 1% or 2% in your slicer.

I had fun making these so please let me know if you like them and post pics, or if there are any changes you'd like I might be able to help there too.

0.1 - 0.2

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Depending on your nozzle size, these may need to be printed with just a single wall, otherwise the fine details on top might not be filled correctly. They will also print best at a resolution of .1
I designed these by scanning a Hi-Res copy of the original tokens, and used that as a base to model them in Fusion 360.

description.text:
Some movement rulers for the X-Wing Miniatures game. These also include the newer movement symbols from the Force Awakens set.

There are 2 versions of these. The standard ones have the symbols on top, and the Alternate ones have them recessed into the rulers if you don't want them sitting on top.

Resolution:

0.1 - 0.2

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Like my X-Wing tokens, these will print the details on top better with just a single wall, depending on your nozzle size. I also recommend printing at .1 resolution if you have the patience.

You may have to print the straight rulers diagonally if they won't fit on your build plate normally. Also if your printer doesn't have a diagonal print area of 300mm or more, you'll have to print the split version of the range ruler.

While I did offset the connector a small amount for the split ranger ruler, you may still need to very lightly sand it down to get it to fit. It should be fairly tight to keep it together, unless you want to glue it.

description.text:
For DIY stirplates for homebrewers.  Get your maximum output from your yeast starter using this stirplate.  Works with those .25" diameter neodynium magnets.  It fits on a 12V computer fan.  
For the stirbar, you'll need to print and pause halfway after the slot is printed, and before the printer closes it up on top.  Just place a bunch of the magnets inside, then continue the print.  
I was unsuccessful mostly because I couldn't get the fan to spin slowly enough for the stir bar.  This, and my flask isn't very flat on the bottom.  It takes the right speed and a 'sweet spot' height for the stirbar.  You might need to scale the z height on the stirplate.stl file to get the right height.  
I'm gonna keep working on getting a speed that isn't too fast, but right now the minimum voltage for this fan seems to high to get a reasonable speed out of it.

For the stirbar, you'll need to print this upside down, with the smaller cross end on the buildplate.  The hollow for the magnets is a U shape inside so you can place in the magnets before it closes up the top.  Don't put the magnets in before the last open layer or you might get interferences with the extrude nozzle.  
For the stirplate_plate, you'll need to reverse polarity on the magnets;  four on one side should be north, four on the other side south.

description.text:
This is a replacement for expensive clip-less pedal systems used on bicycles.  The commercial versions require a special shoe/pedal combination.  This item allows you to use any old shoe, and the existing pedal of your bike.  Your bike does not have to be modified in anyway.  Unfortunately one pair of old sneakers will have to become bike only shoes.
This is an easy way to double your power output when on a bike.  You will be able to apply force on your downward and upward stroke.  I've notice a big difference while using them.
I've biked 30 miles using this system so far this season.  No wear and tear detected.  I'll update this later when I've put more miles on.

Print out two of the plates, one for each shoe / pedal.  I used 1 extra shell and 30 percent infill. 
Lightly sand the connection point, and ensure you can slide the male end through the receiver easily. 
Glue the male end onto the bottom of your shoes, I used plain over the counter krazy glue and it is holding really well
Bolt the female end to your pedal
The goal is to have the balls of your feet inline with the center of the pedal.
You can "snap in" to lock your foot in place by aligning the male female ends and applying pressure.  You will get use to where your foot has to be, some practice is required.
To release your foot apply upward pressure and slide your foot away from the bike.
If you have never used a clip-less pedal system make sure to practice first, if you come to a stop and panic its easy to fall over before you remember to free your feet.

I printed this with PETG since I like the more translucent look as well as the added strength in most applications I have found. I printed a little slower to help with the fine details (about 50mm/s) as well as cranked up the bed temp to help with bed adhesion. No cooling fan was necessary.

When the model is sliced, there should be either 3 or 4 layers on the main body of the bookmark to allow enough material to be strong yet maintain flexibility. More layers may become too stiff. I haven't tried with PLA yet but I plan to adjust if I find any issues arise.

These will accept an M3 nut and then drop into the slot in a 20mm profile t-slot aluminum extrusion (incl. MakerSlide). No need to slide in and out from the ends of the extrusion! Insert a screw and turn clockwise to tighten and it will turn 60Â° to lock in place. Turn counterclockwise to loosen and it slips right out of the slot. I have only tested it with 20mm and 25mm profiles, but it's parametric, and should work with any profile larger than 20mm. If you find settings that work well for other profiles, let me know and I'll update the files.

These are tiny, and the first few iterations didn't work because there was too little material to reliably produce the shape. You'll want to print a lot of them at once for cooling purposes, and the scad file has variables for duplicating it along the X and Y axes.

Kind of an obscure part. This is experimental.

This device plugs into front/left double Shimano brifters, with externally routed cables (i.e. older). It allows double brifters to be used with triple cranksets. See the Sheldon Brown entry here: http://www.sheldonbrown.com/gloss_e-f.html

As far as I know, this device is no longer in production. I personally have wanted to use something like this, so I thought I'd try it out.

Guessed based on pictures here: http://www.sheldonbrown.com/gloss_e-f.html

Pulled measurements off a Shimano RD-M786 for the ferrule insertion point, & a shift ferrule I had lying around. Check my profile to get dimensions for the latter.

The difference between the OD of the carrier & the ID of the brifter mount is 0.5 mm because I didn't want this thing to rattle. As a result, it could be too close.

If you don't understand how this works, read the Sheldon Brown entry, & the procedure in the assembly & materials section. Note that the axial difference in the carrier's position relative to the brifter mount doesn't actually matter, as long as it's sufficient. If it's too slack, then the FD will just slam to the lower limit, which is okay. It'll only be a problem if it slackens the cable too much & the cable catches on something, which I doubt.

Because of the way this works, I guessed how long the cutout needed to be axially, & just wrapped it to half of the circumference of the brifter mount large OD.

As you can see in the wireframe assembly view in the double/triple mode images above, the carrier always has a sufficient insertion depth that it should be hopefully secure.

21 Dec 2016: Current problem is that I need to increase the barrel depth on the brifter mount so the carrier is well supported.

The Solidworks assembly is extremely sensitive to changes right now. If you even spin the parts relative to each other, you will break the brifter mount SLDPRT. I'm not sure why.

I will probably just redo the entire brifter mount part.

22 Dec 2016: Fixed all the parts now. Check the double mode & triple mode images. Now the design should be a lot more robust.

I also realized the flipping the switch may not do anything. If the cable tension is high enough, then the carrier will be pressed too hard against the brifter mount & they'll rotate together. Unless you use both hands to force them to turn relative to each other, it won't actually work.

However, there's no way to find out if this will be a real issue until it's tested.

As of now, I don't have any immediate plans for try this on any of my bikes. If you do test this, let me know how it goes.

As such, this project will be listed as "work-in-progress" indefinitely until someone tests it, or I do, whoever does it first & gets back to me.

I'm also concerned about the 4 mm diameter of the switch. The bigger it is, the stronger it is, but it also enlarges the cutout necessary to engage the triple mode.

Installation is simple:

1) Insert carrier into brifter mount.
2) Insert this assembly into the brifter ferrule port.
3) Set the carrier to be into the "double" position on the brifter mount (see image above).
4) Install shifter cable & housing, & adjust as necessary. You should now be able to use only the middle & large ring.
5) Flip the switch to sink the carrier into the brifter mount, thereby releasing tension & allowing the FD to access the small ring.
6) Adjust lower limit as necessary.

Filing may be required for these interfaces:

  • OD of carrier & ID of brifter mount. Clearance is 0.5 mm right now
  • small OD of brifter mount & ID of brifter ferrule port
  • brifter mount length that inserts into the brifter (could be too long)
  • the transition between the slide & the "double" position: only if that notch is too deeply set in for your taste. Too undefined & the slide will slip/engage frequently. Too defined & it'll be difficult to engage the triple mode.

Hopefully I'll work up a better mount at some point, but probably won't bother until this one breaks since it works for me for now.

I whipped this up in openscad with measurements based off of allted's original design with modifications to fit the knife holder I got off banggood. Openscad files included and improvements are strongly encouraged. The _v2 version is the one I'm actually using.

This is a slight modification to allow mounting atop the "supa flat" x-carriage from Aleph Objects.  It needed a 60mm bolt spacing.

Slic3r will only generate the cone part of this object for extrusion width ratios over a certain value for some reason (2.77 in my case).  The cone will clear the x-axis rods under the supa-flat carriage, but could be cut back some to improve air flow (the cone restricts air flow a lot).  I removed most of the upper half near the end for better air flow.
The cone also hangs too low for my makergear groovemount setup.  It needs a spacer under the bracket to raise it about 3mm.  The spacer bar is to lift it up that much.  Stacks of 3mm washers could be used too (6 of them make 3mm).  This does get in the way of removing the big gear on my Wade's extruder, too.
Print the spacer bar, and the fan mount.  Replace the front screws of the supa flat carriage bearing retainer with longer ones. Mount the spacer bar, then the bracket with washers and nuts on the longer screws (3mm x 25mm).
VERIFY before using it that the fan cone is higher than your extruder tip, or it will collide with your prints.

As it is hard to provide complete files since it depends on your machine setup, this is more of a contribution to spark some ideas if someone are interested. A fun project!

Base part was made from an old oak countertop I had lying around. White parts made from some pinewood.

  1. First I leveled the oak plate on top and bottom, then measured the heigth of the plate to program the milling
  2. Did the carving of all numbers and chamfering
  3. Milled out the holes for the white parts, then cut out the piece. I chose to go down 12mm for the whiteparts
  4. Cut out the whiteparts (first leveled the pinewood to 12.2 mm.
  5. Used wood glue on the white parts and knocked them into place.
  6. Sanding. Lot of it!
  7. Since the oak plate was old and probably had a high level of moisture the plate started bending slightly when I cut it out. So some of the holes for the white parts was slightly off. I therefore made some wood filler from the sanding and filled in all minor gaps plus the numbers/letters
  8. Sanding again :D
  9. Oiled the thing - finito!

Hope you like it :D

description.text:
The VW Beetle is one the best selling cars in the world. Over 21 million cars were built by the German manufacturer Volkswagen. It's streamline shape, the air cooled engine with the distinctive sound and the trunk in the front are the most noticeable features.

My build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute. I used 6 mm beech plywood and 6 mm beech rods for the the axles. I added a little bit of grease to improve the rotation, washers give the tires (darkened with wood stained) a proper displacement.

A laser cutter might be a good alternative tool to build this model. Consider that some sophisticated parts need a certain size and/or material to be strong enough.

description.text:
Brushless Tiny Whoop

Duct for each motor printed as separate part, so if you break one you don't have to print entire frame.

Print each part twice and put everything together like this:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ICViKRukXuo

Designed for following parts:

Motors: Racerstar 1103 8000kv/10000kv
Propeller: DYS 2030
Flight controller: Pico BLX (20mm x 20mm mounting holes)
ESC: 4in1 racerstar 6A (20mm x 20mm)
Battery: 2s

Finished product should look like this:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j3msxzyWhr4

3d printed:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rPKuajP53lA

Added 3-inch version (77.5mm inner diameter)

Haven’t printed it yet so I don’t know if it is sturdy enough.

  • Duct wall is 0.8mm tick – two layers if using 0.4mm nozzle
  • Angled struts
  • Slots for motor wires. Braking duct doesn’t require disordering

Added 40mm version (41mm inner diameter)

Haven’t printed it yet so I don’t know if it is sturdy enough.

  • Duct wall is 0.8mm tick – two layers if using 0.4mm nozzle
  • Angled struts
  • Slots for motor wires. Braking duct doesn’t require disordering

Added 50mm version2 (48mm inner diameter)

Haven’t printed it yet so I don’t know if it is sturdy enough.

  • Duct wall is 0.8mm tick – two layers if using 0.4mm nozzle
  • Angled struts
  • Slots for motor wires. Braking duct doesn’t require disordering

Added 3-inch full FC version (77.5mm inner diameter)

Haven’t printed it yet so I don’t know if it is sturdy enough.

  • Duct wall is 0.8mm tick – two layers if using 0.4mm nozzle
  • Angled struts
  • Slots for motor wires. Braking duct doesn’t require disordering
  • 30x30mm FC mounting holes

Added 53mm version (53mm inner diameter)

Turns out that DYS 2030 propeller is 53mm in diameter (and not 47mm as stated on Banggood site). So new version was in order...

  • Duct wall is 0.8mm tick – two layers if using 0.4mm nozzle
  • Angled struts
  • Slots for motor wires. Braking duct doesn’t require disordering
  • Recommended props DYS 2030
